&lt;p&gt;This is a snippet of code from my FullStackFutures web application. And here I implement a feature of Express.js Routing Mechanism, &lt;em&gt;Route Handlers&lt;/em&gt; (&lt;strong&gt;profileRouter&lt;/strong&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;Route Handler&lt;/strong&gt; is code that is looking for a request to a specific incoming URL such as &lt;em&gt;&quot;/login&quot;&lt;/em&gt; and often a specific HTTP verb such as POST and has specific code for handling that precise URL and verb. - &lt;strong&gt;stack overflow&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This route &lt;em&gt;(&quot;/api/profiles/all&quot;)&lt;/em&gt; responds to an API GET request from the client. The API request is calling for the server to not only return all profile documents in the application&apos;s MongoDB collection, &lt;em&gt;profiles&lt;/em&gt;, but also ensure the user is logged in and authenticated to access this route. Let&apos;s swipe up and see the remainder of the profileRouter.&lt;/p&gt;
